{"key":"post-10680496","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10680496</id>\n<content>Most experienced growers and all commercial growers use grains.&amp;nbsp; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/BRF-Pf-Tek&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;BRF&lt;/a&gt; is great for learning the ropes and is more forgiving.&amp;nbsp; In addition, BRF doesn't require a pressure cooker, and you can get away without a laminar flow hood by following good sterile technique with a glovebox.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;However, brf is the fastest way to go from spores to fruits, hands down.&amp;nbsp; That's why we recommend it for first time growers.&amp;nbsp; If after a grow or two, you decide the hobby isn't for you, your investment is small.&amp;nbsp; If you decide it's what you want to pursue, switch to grains and bulk growing.&amp;nbsp; There's no dishonor in using cakes.&amp;nbsp; I wish they had been around when I was learning the ropes.&amp;nbsp; I still use cakes for proving strains after doing a series of strain isolations, simply because it's the fastest method of getting fruits.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10680632</next>\n<prev>10680337</prev>\n<first>10679901</first>\n<last>10701422</last>\n<when>1247670455</when>\n<utime>07/15/09 06:07 PM</utime>\n</post>"}